<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 94 / Regulator may be shifting on prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Offer, the electricity industry regulator, is showing signs of compromise in
talks with regional power companies over its plans for a tough regulatory
framework from next April.
However, the companies say the latest letter from Professor Stephen
Littlechild, Offer director-general, suggests there is still a wide gap
between his views on distribution prices and theirs.
'The general tone is that he is prepared to consider some of the problems
the industry has put to him,' said one chief executive. 'But he is still
being extremely stringent and our initial evaluation is that if he made his
final proposals now we would find them unacceptable.'
Some analysts expecting a compromise were also encouraged by remarks by
Norweb which reported annual results yesterday. Mr Ken Harvey, chairman,
said he could say nothing about the contents of Prof Littlechild's letter
but he confirmed that his company still expected to be able to offer real
dividend growth of 6 to 8 per cent annually until the end of the decade.
Some City houses believe Norweb would struggle to do so if the regulator
stuck to the tough line taken in his letter earlier in the summer which was
interpreted as suggesting distribution price cuts of up to 20 per cent
initially and rises of inflation minus 4 per cent in subsequent years.
Most analysts believe the final cuts will be less tough, although UBS
believes Prof Littlechild is unlikely to move significantly.
Prof Littlechild's letter of was faxed to companies on Friday evening amid
tight security precautions.
Norweb and Seeboard results, Page 22
</TEXT>
