<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 94 / Gummer pressed on nature quango
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, is under pressure to disclose
whether directors of English Nature, the government's nature conservation
watchdog, face potential conflicts of interest with posts that they hold in
the private sector.
Mr Chris Smith, shadow environment secretary, yesterday confirmed that he
had tabled a written parliamentary question to Mr Gummer, asking him to
outline the guidelines that exist for appointments to English Nature and
other Department of Environment quangos.
Mr Smith is raising the issue amid concern over the role of Lord Cranbrook,
a Conservative peer, who has been chairman of English Nature since 1991.
Lord Cranbrook is chairman of the environmental advisory board of Shanks and
McEwan, the waste disposal company, and has been a non-executive director of
Anglia Water since 1989.
Mr Smith said yesterday: 'I am sure there has been no specific conflict of
interest that has affected any decision at English Nature. But I want to
assure the public that this is the case.
'If it turns out that there are guidelines for such an appointment, I would
be interested to know what they are. If not, then that may be a cause of
concern.'
The government will shortly be putting fresh proposals to Ms Clare
Spottiswoode, the gas industry regulator, to fund the Energy Savings Trust,
Mr Gummer said yesterday.
He told the environment select committee that the proposals would be 'very
detailed', and would be based on recommendations from a group he had set up
to look at the options. Last spring, Ms Spottiswoode startled the committee
by saying she did not think it was her role to impose a levy on gas
consumers to fund the trust, which is central to the government's strategy
to conserve energy and reduce harmful emissions.
He also said the UK would be able to exceed the target it has set itself to
return carbon dioxide emissions to their 1990 level by the year 2000.
</TEXT>
