<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 94 / Peers resist Lloyd's regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lord Henley, a government spokesman, told the House of Lords last night that
no case had been made for bringing any element of the Lloyd's insurance
market under the provisions of the Financial Services Act.
He resisted an amendment to the deregulation and contracting-out bill which
sought to end the self-regulation practised by Lloyd's under the terms of
private legislation approved by parliament in 1982.
Lord Williams of Elvel, who moved the amendment from the Labour front bench,
said there was a question mark over the future of Lloyd's as a result of
losses which could be attributed to incompetence and the failure of
self-regulation.
He said that if the amendment were approved it would put the insurance and
reinsurance activities carried out under the Lloyd's umbrella on a sure
footing for the future.
Lord Marlesford, the only Conservative peer who took part in the debate to
speak in favour of the amendment, described himself as a 'victim' of
Lloyd's. He said it was an act of myopia which had led parliament to grant
Lloyd's immunity from the Financial Services Act.
Lord Marlesford suggested that a future ruling by the courts could result in
the minutes of the Lloyd's council being disclosed and the extent to which
it had failed to protect Names being revealed.
He criticised the way in which Lloyd's had 'hypothecated' profits for 1994
to meet the losses of 1991.
He also called for an assurance that the Department of Trade and Industry
would discharge its responsibility for determining the solvency of Lloyd's.
Lord Williams withdrew the amendment, but indicated that he may return to
the issue at a later stage of the bill.
</TEXT>
