<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 94 / Law urged on discrimination against disabled
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party's Commission on Social Justice yesterday called for
legislation to outlaw discrimination against the disabled.
In a policy paper, the commission also called for research into a system of
income-boosting payments, reflecting disabled people's drastically reduced
earning capacity and extra costs of daily life.
Sir Gordon Borrie, the commission chairman, said: 'Disabled people are an
untapped resource of energy and ideas. We need a big shift in attitudes and
policies to tap their talent.'
The paper was written by commission member Mr Bert Massie, director of the
Royal Association for Disability and Rehabilitation.
Mr Massie says: 'The first principle of equality for disabled people should
be comprehensive anti-discrimination legislation.'
His paper, Disabled People and Social Justice, also called for:
Research into special payments.
'No fault' compensation, so disablement claims can be handled faster.
Disabled to be able to choose local authority services or the cash
equiva-lent.
Full involvement of disabled in policy-making.
According to government figures, the UK has 6.5m disabled people.
Out of this total an estimated 70 per cent of those of working age are not
employed, and fewer than one in three companies meets the quota that 3 per
cent of workers in companies employing 20 or more be disabled.
The paper says: 'Few people will reach their grave without experiencing
impairment or disability. Public policies which are perceived to favour
disabled people are in fact policies for everyone - not policies for 'them'
but policies for 'us'.'
It says legislation is not 'the whole answer' to disabled people's problems,
and highlighted the importance of healthcare provision, housing and
transport design.
Disabled People and Social Justice. Institute for Public Policy Research,
30-32 Southampton Street, London WC2E 7RA. Pounds 2.95 including postage.
</TEXT>
