<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 94 / Unit trust savings continue to flow in
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Savers continued to invest in unit trusts last month in spite of uncertain
market conditions.
Figures from the Association of Unit Trusts and Investment Funds showed a
net inflow of Pounds 726m, of which 87 per cent came from private investors.
The figure is down from last May's inflow of Pounds 915m, but well above
1990-92 levels; 1993 was a record year for the unit trust industry, with net
investment of Pounds 9.1bn.
Mr Philip Warland, the association's director-general, said the figures
pointed to a healthy change in saving habits, as investors appeared to be
ignoring short-term market movements and investing for the long term.
The growth of regular savings schemes, particularly via personal equity
plans, also contributed to a steadier flow of money into trusts.
Trusts in the UK equity income and UK growth sectors were most popular with
private investors during the month, attracting Pounds 124m and Pounds 111m
respectively.
There are now more than 1m unit holders of UK equity income trusts.
Among institutional investors, funds shifted out of the Far East excluding
Japan, and European sectors, and into Japanese trusts in May. Japanese
trusts were also popular with private investors, attracting a total of
Pounds 158m net new money.
Unit trusts now have a total of Pounds 95bn under management, down from the
peak of almost Pounds 100bn in January this year, before most stock markets
started to fall.
