<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 94 / Companies House wins appeal case
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies House, the govern-ment's corporate information depository,
yesterday an-nounced that it had won a significant legal victory in attempts
to impose its penalties for the late-filing of company accounts.
The organisation, which is an executive agency of the Department of Trade
and Industry under the Next Steps programme, won on appeal a court case
against an arbitration. A company - Livepine - had initially succeeded in
overturning a Pounds 100 late-filing penalty after it missed the deadline
when Companies House rejected the accounts it initially submitted.
The company had failed to sign the directors' report in its accounts, and
argued in its defence that this was not required under section 242 of the
1985 Companies Act.
However, the Basingstoke court demanded that the fine be paid, arguing that
the wider context of the act required that the report must be signed.
Companies House allows companies submitting incomplete filings 14 days to
make modifications and re-file the accounts to avoid penalties. Most
companies have 10 months after their financial year-ends during which to
file. Late filing penalties were introduced in 1992 in response to
politicians' concerns over the high proportion of companies filing many
months after the legal date had expired.
Last month Mr David Durham, chief executive, told the Commons committee on
the parliamentary commissioner for administration that Companies House had
handled 65,000 disputes since the regime was introduced - the volume of
calls and letters was greater than he had anticipated.
Mr William Reed, the parliamentary commissioner - or ombudsman - said he had
completed examinations of two cases concerning Companies House in 1993 and a
further six were still under investigation. By that time, 164,000 penalties
had been imposed on companies, generating fines of Pounds 33m, which are
remitted to the Treasury. The annual administrative cost of running the late
penalty regime is Pounds 1.3m.
</TEXT>
