<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 94 / Revenue confesses to tax errors: Underestimates total Pounds
430m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Taxpayers paid up to Pounds 100m less in tax than they owed to the Inland
Revenue last year, the Commons public accounts committee heard yesterday.
Sir Anthony Battishill, chairman of the Board of Inland Revenue, told MPs
errors in Revenue calculations of assessments sent to taxpayers had
underestimated Pounds 100m tax from Schedule D (self-employed) and Pounds
330m from Schedule E (pay-as-you-earn) taxpayers.
These gross figures were offset by assessments for too much tax of Pounds
70m for Schedule D taxpayers and Pounds 260m for those under Schedule E.
Sir Anthony was answering questions following publication earlier this month
of a highly critical report on tax administration by the National Audit
Office, the Whitehall watchdog.
The report highlighted the fact that of the 5m taxpayers who receive
assessments each year the figures were incorrect for 3.1m of those on
Schedule D and more than 0.1m on Schedule E.
Many of the errors were caused by taxpayer mistakes, but 10 per cent - or
500,000 - were the fault of the Inland Revenue, and in many of these cases
it was the taxpayer rather than the Revenue who identified the
miscalculation.
Sir Anthony stressed yesterday that the difference between assessments and
the correct level of tax was just one-tenth of 1 per cent, and said the
Revenue had introduced a quality division to improve accuracy and ensure
taxpayers paid the right amount.
However, he said he was not satisfied with the current position. 'Any errors
that get people's tax wrong are to be regretted,' he said.
He also admitted that 'morale is not as good as it has been in the past'
among Revenue staff as they adjusted to periods of tremendous change and
uncertainty.
Mr Michael Stern, Conservative MP for Bristol North West, expressed
scepticism over the Revenue's belief that most taxpayers truly wanted to pay
the correct amount of tax, as they had stated in surveys commissioned by the
Revenue.
He said that in his experience as a chartered accountant taxpayers were
extremely reluctant to push for a revised assessment if they had been asked
by the Revenue to pay less tax than was due.
The issue is important because the new system of self-assessment places the
onus on taxpayers to calculate how much tax they pay, and the Revenue
generally to accept this figure unquestioned.
The National Audit Office report also pointed out that just 60 per cent of
taxpayers surveyed said they were satisfied with the Revenue's handling of
correspondence.
</TEXT>
