<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 94 / Dobson backs rail union's claim
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Frank Dobson, shadow transport secretary, yesterday moved Labour close to
outright public support for the series of one-day rail strikes mounted by
the RMT transport union.
Mr Dobson told the RMT annual conference in Liverpool that the signalmen at
the heart of the dispute 'think they have been swindled; they are right.'
He added: 'The government has been demanding that Labour should condemn the
strike. We refuse to condemn it. Workers who are being swindled out of their
wages have a fundamental human right to withdraw their labour.'
Mr Dobson was careful not to express explicit support for the strikes, which
have brought most of the rail network to a standstill on the past two
Wednesdays.
But he said Labour would 'continue to support the signal workers' claim . .
. not as some fix or favour. They will get our support because their claim
is just.'
Mr Dobson's comments point to a stronger line in support of the strikes by
shadow ministers, who have hitherto sought to avoid being too closely
identified with the strikes.
Labour MPs have been heartened by indications that many rail travellers
blame the strikes on government interference in negotiations between RMT and
Railtrack, the state-owned infrastructure company.
Mr Dobson also said Labour would 'reverse the break-up and privatisation of
the railways, and bring the system, the whole system, back under public
ownership and control.'
His comments strengthened Labour's commitment to renationalisation, which
has previously been restricted to those parts of the network still in state
ownership.
Renationalisation of the 'whole system' would be expensive if it meant
purchasing train operating companies sold to the private sector before the
next general election. But Labour officials said Mr Dobson's pledge was
subject to the shadow cabinet's agreement that all spending promises would
depend on available resources.
Mr Dobson accused the government of prolonging the dispute, and claimed that
a settlement could be financed from the millions of pounds being
'squandered' on privatisation.
'For years, signalling staff have contributed massive improvements in
productivity - accepting new technology and the changes in working practices
that go with it,' he said.
For two years, RMT negotiators had been told that an agreement rewarding the
signallers for past productivity gains would be concluded when Railtrack
took over track and signalling responsibilities in April.
Mr Dobson claimed that a settlement rewarding signalmen for productivity
gains would not breach the government's public sector pay policy, set out by
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, in September.
Observer, Page 19
</TEXT>
