FT  28 JUN 94 / Three counties to hear fate today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The High Court will rule today on Avon, Cleveland and Somerset county
councils' applications for judicial review of proposals that they should be
abolished. The move comes as legal challenges to the English local
government review intensify.
If any of today's applications succeed, the credibility of the Local
Government Commission for England, chaired by Sir John Banham, could be
critically damaged in the week before it announces recommendations for
restructuring 16 more counties.
It could also open the way for more legal action, as several counties
already recommended for abolition are considering applying for judicial
review, and would be encouraged by any successes today.
Buckinghamshire, which was recommended for abolition two weeks ago, to be
replaced by three unitary authorities, is seeking 'top legal opinion' over
what it says 'appear to be serious inadequacies in a leaflet being
distributed to households in the county by the commission'.
The leaflet is central to the commission's attempt to gauge public opinion
in the area in the final stage of its consultation. But Mr Kenneth Ross,
council chairman, said the commission's concern that services would be
'fragmented' under the new structure, included in its formal report, had
been excluded from the leaflet.
Districts in Cumbria, which will be split into two large unitary authorities
under current proposals, are also discussing legal action against the
proposals. In Cambridgeshire, both the county and several districts are also
planning legal action over the commission's refusal to include the two-tier
status quo as an option.
</TEXT>
