FT  28 JUN 94 / MoD cuts beat Treasury needs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Ministry of Defence will next month announce cuts in military
expenditure well in excess of those required by the Treasury in the current
financial year, according to defence sources.
The MoD is required to shave around Pounds 750m off its budget for the
financial year 1994-95 to meet the targets set out in the last Budget.
Officials drawing together about 30 separate reports for the Defence Cost
Studies project have discovered far more room for cuts in military support
services than had been expected.
In the run up to the publication of the Defence Cost Studies, MoD officials
are arguing with the Treasury over whether the extra expenditure saved will
be retained by the department.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary, will want to announce several
'sweeteners' when the cuts in support services are announced, probably on
July 14.
Backbench Conservative MPs have expressed anxiety about the projected cuts
in military support services - such as hospitals and non-military transport
 -arguing that these will undermine the military's front-line capability.
While they accept that some support services can be reduced, some MPs have
argued that the army needs more land-based helicopters, tanks and stores of
ammunition.
As a sign of their concern over the issue, the defence select committee has
agreed, insisting that it will re-convene in the summer recess, if
necessary, to discuss the Defence Cost Studies proposals. A meeting outside
a parliamentary sitting would be almost unprecedented.
