FT  28 JUN 94 / Bottomley attacks 'federalist dreams'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mrs Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, yesterday underlined the
growing appeal of anti-federalist thinking in the Conservative party by
endorsing the prime minister's recent statements on Europe.
Mrs Bottomley has traditionally been associated with the centrist and
pro-European part of the Tory party. But in a surprisingly Euro-sceptic
speech she attacked the 'pied pipers of federalism', saying they were
'losing their followers, even in countries where their ideas were once so
applauded'.
Delivering the Alison Tennant Memorial lecture in London, Mrs Bottomley said
the institutions of Europe needed to forget their 'centralist and federalist
dreams'.
She applauded the prime minister's recent call for a multi-speed,
multi-track Europe, saying that it was an idea that appealed far beyond the
British Conservative party.
'Some have argued that the only way to consolidate Europe's achievements is
to roll forward towards ever closer economic and political integration,' she
said. 'That view is misguided. The voters have rumbled it. Increasingly the
call is for nations to build Europe, not for Europe to supersede nations.'
