<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 94 / World Trade News: Brown in Brazil to boost US business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Raytheon Company of Massachusetts yesterday received a boost in its hotly
contested bid for a multi-billion-dollar Brazilian radar project with the
visit to Latin America of Mr Ron Brown, US commerce secretary.
The SIVAM project for the Amazon is a combination anti-drug, air traffic
control and environmental scheme, also sought by Alcatel/Thompson of France.
The first phase of the project alone is worth an estimated Dollars
1bn-Dollars 1.5bn.
Mr Dennis Picard, Raytheon chairman, is among the 22 company heads
accompanying Mr Brown on his trade and investment mission. Also in the
delegation is Mr Arthur Pilzer, a vice president with the US Export-Import
Bank.
Mr Pilzer said the US was determined to offer a competitive finance package
consistent with the rules agreed by the industrialised countries. At one
point yesterday the delegation was in touch with Mr Kenneth Brody, Eximbank
chairman, in Washington.
Mr Brown, who successfully lobbied Saudi Arabia for two multi-billion-dollar
contracts for aircraft and telecommunications, has made export promotion a
key tenet of the administration's foreign policy. He was on the telephone
yesterday with President Bill Clinton, who was also brought into the bidding
effort for the Saudi contracts.
Mr Brown has been telling his Brazilian hosts in Rio de Janeiro and Sao
Paulo the US 'intends to compete and win'.
Part statesman, part preacher and part politician, Mr Brown is a powerful
sign of US interest in a country which needs to get its currency under
control. He races from meetings to receptions to briefings in a cavalcade of
cars and vans, accompanied by sirens and leather-jacketed motorcycle police.
To stress the importance of raising living standards, he visited two
impoverished neighbourhoods. He headed two soccer balls at a neighbourhood
centre, supported by Xerox. At a school he sat on a small chair listening to
a boy stumble as he read to him.
Mr Fernando Opitz, Rio Stock Exchange vice chairman, has seen US officials
promote 'partnership' between US and Brazil for years. 'We've never seen
anything like this before,' he said.
Mr Pilzer announced that the Eximbank was ready to lend money to Brazilian
state-owned companies. 'We view Brazil as a market we could do a lot of
business in within a few years,' he said.
The Eximbank has not lent Brazil or its state-owned companies money for at
least eight years.
</TEXT>
