<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUN 94 / Turnout high for Ukraine election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JILL BARSHAY and CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Ukrainians turned out in large numbers yesterday for their first
post-independence presidential election. Preliminary results early this
morning suggested the vote would go to a second round between the incumbent,
Mr Leonid Kravchuk, and Mr Leonid Kuchma, the former prime minister, in two
weeks' time.
Early reports from several polling stations throughout Ukraine indicated
that Mr Kuchma had made a strong showing in the more Russified eastern
regions of the country and Crimea but this had been offset by Mr Kravchuk's
popularity in the centre and the west. Mr Oleksandr Moroz, the hardline
socialist chairman of parliament, was running a weak third.
Turnout was reported to be 68 per cent of the 38m voters. Results were
expected later today.
Opinion polls on the eve of the elections suggested Mr Kravchuk had
undergone a transformation, from the man who destroyed Ukraine's economy, to
the only leader who could guarantee the country's stability.
Manipulating state television with considerable skill, he seemed in recent
weeks to have successfully reshaped the national debate. Now, instead of
being about repairing the economy, it is about maintaining national
independence.
