<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUN 94 / World Bond Markets: London
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
With no significant UK economic data due this week, international factors
are set to play a key role in the gilt markets. In the aftermath of the
Fed's apparently unsuccessful attempt to defend the dollar on Friday, the
international bond climate seems set to remain both bearish and volatile.
This is expected to have a knock-on effect on gilts, not least because UK
bonds are currently closely reflecting developments in continental European
bond markets such as Germany.
On the domestic front, the main event of the week will be the Bank of
England's Pounds 2bn auction on Wednesday of a floating-rate Treasury 1999
issue. With the size slightly lower than the Pounds 2.5bn of the last FRG
issue, some analysts, like Mr Nigel Richardson of Yamaichi International,
argue that this indicates the Treasury is revising down its expectation for
the public sector borrowing requirement.
Other traders disagree. and argue that it is too early in the financial year
to forecast a change in the level of government borrowing.
Either way, the release of the Treasury forecast on Tuesday, which will
include a PSBR prediction for this year, will be scrutinised by the gilts
market. The forecast is expected to show that expectations of inflation have
been revised down and those of growth rates up.
</TEXT>
