<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUN 94 / Dealing with a Welsh Pandora's box: Roland Adburgham reports
on a turbulent year for the chairman of the WDA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When the National Audit Office last week praised the Welsh Development
Agency's programme of land reclamation Mr David Rowe-Beddoe, the agency's
chairman, was visibly relieved that at last someone had said a kind word.
He ruefully noted that in the turbulent 12 months since he took over as
chairman on July 1 last year the media have almost invariably described the
WDA as 'much-troubled' or 'scandal-ridden'.
A Cardiff-born international businessman, he was aware at the time of his
appointment by the Welsh secretary that the WDA 'had a very successful
reputation and was the positive envy of much of the UK, and of similar
development agencies overseas'. He also knew that there had been 'an
auditing problem' and that a report by the Commons public accounts committee
was imminent.
Mr Rowe-Beddoe did not realise that what he called 'a Pandora's box' was
about to open. The MPs' report on the 1990-91 accounts said standards at the
agency had been 'well below' what parliament had a right to expect. It
unleashed a series of damaging stories with the agency depicted as an
example of the lack of accountability of quangos.
Mr Rowe-Beddoe said: 'My immediate response to the public accounts committee
report was that we would accept it in its entirety.' An external inquiry was
set up and its recommendations adopted. Mr Philip Head, the chief executive,
resigned. The chairman said that the problems shown by the report had been
cured. But it remains his task to rebuild the agency's reputation, while
proving that 'we are committed to maintaining the highest probity in the
management of the taxpayers' funds in this agency'.
Since he arrived - taking over from Dr Gwyn Jones, who headed the agency for
five years - there have been new board members and senior managers have been
recruited from outside. The agency itself is in the throes of being reshaped
into a slimmer structure with a smaller head office in Cardiff and more
staff in the regions. About 60 of the 400 employees are being made
redundant, adding to staff demoralisation. The chairman described it as a
'painful time'.
Mr Rowe-Beddoe was adamant that the reorganisation was in response to a
changing business environment and not the PAC report. 'My own thinking would
have been crystallised without any PAC frame in which to be operating - just
from the natural consequences of going out and talking to our marketplace.
'I set out last year to visit as many parts of Wales as possible and meet
with the people who really represented our customer base. A popular
perception was that all the agency did was to market inward investment,
whereas the reality is that a substantial majority of our budget (Pounds
170m) is spent in Wales. There were such comments as all roads appeared to
begin and end in Cardiff, and the further away from the centre, the longer
for any decision to be taken.'
What was clear, he said, was that the agency's focus needed to be sharpened
towards the delivery of services. Three domestic divisions were being
created in the north, south and west, with more delegated authority.
The agency's effectiveness, he said, had to be measured by the creation of
jobs. Of the means to achieve that, 'inward investment is clearly a vitally
important aspect of continuing economic growth'. He emphasised the amount of
expansion by existing inward investors, with some Japanese companies
re-investing five times or more.
While land reclamation and urban renewal continued to be priorities, a shift
of emphasis was to provide more support for indigenous companies. 'They have
felt in the past that because they weren't Japanese or American they weren't
getting attention. That is being rectified. The small and medium-size
enterprises are our greatest potential strength for the future,' he said.
The question remains however: how long will the WDA be haunted by the past?
This month Mr Barry Hartop, appointed chief executive in March, notified the
public accounts committee of apparently unauthorised redundancy payments in
the 1980s. Mr Rowe-Beddoe did not dispute that further matters could come to
light.
'But if you think we are spending our life in a witch-hunt, forget it. That
isn't what we are doing,' he said. 'What we are committed to ensure is that
the housekeeping of today is beyond reproach.'
Mr Rowe-Beddoe denied being dispirited by the criticism. 'A few months ago I
would probably have been dispirited. I think one's skin has grown a little
thicker, and I realise very clearly the accountability of being in the
public sector.'
</TEXT>
