<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUN 94 / Accountancy dips its toe in corporate water: KPMG's look at
restructuring could be part of a trend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When the UK's largest accountancy firms announced their latest fee-income
results earlier this month Mr Ian Brindle, senior partner of Price
Waterhouse, predicted that incorporation was eventually inevitable in the
profession.
Little was he to know how quickly his thoughts might come true, as a group
in rival KPMG Peat Marwick's top management was already considering that
option.
This Friday the most senior partners in KPMG are set to debate options for
the future structure of their firm, which may lead to one of the most
radical restructurings of the profession since its historical roots in the
last century.
If it goes through, the firm would for the first time be able to gain some
protection of partners' personal assets. In exchange there would be both tax
implications and the requirement for public filing of information -
including financial results.
The main reason for incorporation is seen to be an attempt to protect the
firms from the growing number of legal actions seeking redress for alleged
negligent advice.
Although it has never happened a claim can theoretically lead to the
forfeiture of both the property, cash and other assets of the firm, and of
all the individual assets of each of its partners - as its owners, all of
them have unlimited liability. In a company the shareholders have no such
commitment.
Some have also argued that a significant driving force towards change is the
tax system. In the next three years changes instituted by the Inland Revenue
will mean that partnerships will have to move towards paying taxes on a
'current-year' basis - they would no longer be able to defer their payments
to future years. At the very least, this change removes one of the
attractions of partnership.
Incorporation is not simply being considered in the UK. In the US, where the
liability crisis facing accountants is much more serious, all the larger
firms are at an advance stage of preparation for change.
Most are expected to take advantage of laws in Delaware, which will allow
them to register as limited partnerships, protecting their assets across the
country - at least as far as this state's rules are accepted by the courts
in other states.
Yet in the UK there has been little sign so far of incorporation. Under
by-laws issued by the ethical committee of the chartered accountancy
institutes, firms have for many years been able to provide certain services
through companies, notably data processing and management consultancy.
More recently changes introduced in the 1989 Companies Act and in
professional ethical rules amended in late 1991 have meant that all services
provided by accountancy firms - including the core audit function - can be
provided through companies.
Firms that are incorporated can exploit laxer regulation. For example, to
use the title 'chartered accountants' they need only ensure that
three-quarters of the voting rights of the firm are held by chartered
accountants. For partnerships, chartered accountants must also comprise
three-quarters by number of those in charge.
Yet the up-take remains small. Figures from the Institute of Chartered
Accountants in England and Wales show that of 19,409 practitioner firms and
individuals, 192 operate through companies.
One reason may be a reluctance by the firms to disclose their fee income -
something they have always been able to keep secret in spite of growing
calls for greater accountability.
Another is tax. Partners in a company would be required to pay at least an
additional 10 per cent in National Insurance contributions on top of their
existing income taxes.
They could avoid this if they received their income in dividends rather than
salary. But some fear a future Labour government might introduce a new
dividend tax which would prove at least as costly.
An internal briefing paper prepared last year by the largest eight UK firms
in response to the audit liability crisis said that incorporation was no
solution, because partners could still be sued in their personal capacity.
KPMG is nevertheless looking at options involving a more complex structure
than pure incorporation. By having a series of subsidiaries with a range of
legal structures, and most partners as shareholders rather than directors,
most may be able to protect personal assets.
Those directly involved in work for which they are subsequently sued could
still be sued personally.
One thing is certain. KPMG's rivals will be watching its actions over the
next few weeks with considerable interest. They all have a personal stake in
the outcome.
Option to incorporate, Page 25
</TEXT>
<XX>
