<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUN 94 / Work training onus is urged on employees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tax-free savings accounts for individuals to fund their learning should be
permitted in order to stimulate the development of new skills in the UK, a
training and enterprise council report has recommended to the government.
The vehicle for savings, which might be jointly funded with employers, could
be on the line of an educational Tessa, to which parents, individuals and
employers could contribute, says the report from a working group chaired by
Mr Colin Harris, chairman of Surrey Tec and managing director of Legal and
General Financial Services.
The report, etitled Individuals' Commitment to Lifetime Learning, comes as
both Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary, and the Labour party are
looking at ways in which individuals can be encouraged to take more control
of their own learning. The government prefers voluntary incentives while
Labour, which is developing its training policies, is examing whether it
should be obligatory for employers to open an individual training account
for employees requesting one.
The report from the Tec working group, which has been submitted to Mr Hunt,
concludes that individuals play only a minor role in managing their own
learning and that without increased commitment from individuals the UK will
not improve its skills levels sufficiently quickly to meet international
competition.
At present most learning is carried out within the formal educational system
and is undertaken when people are below the age of 22.
The report recommends:
An awareness-raising campaign to highlight the importance of lifetime
learning and the benefits it can bring in terms of job security, career
opportunities and pay.
Tax-free savings accounts for individuals.
Better access for high quality information and advice. Educational providers
to be more flexible in offering training which meets an individual's work
and social needs.
</TEXT>
