<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUN 94 / PosTel vote threatens top company directors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Directors of some of Britain's largest quoted companies are facing the
embarrassing prospect of PosTel, the investment management group, voting
against them at annual meetings this summer.
Inquiries by the Financial Times show that directors of at least four
companies in the FT-SE 100 will have PosTel voting against their election or
re-election at AGMs next month.
The first high-profile case is likely to be Mr Sipko Huismans, chief
executive of Courtaulds, who is up for re-election on July 19.
Last week PosTel's chief executive, Mr Alastair Ross Goobey, said that the
fund management group would be voting against the election and re-election
of directors who had rolling employment contracts longer than two years.
The announcement followed mounting frustration among institutional
shareholders over pay outs of up to three times basic salary to directors on
three-year rolling contracts who are forced to resign.
A fund manager said yesterday: 'It is going to be a long hot summer for some
of the City's biggest names.'
There are at least 133 directors from 29 companies in the FT-SE 100 who are
on three-year rolling contracts. These include 13 executive directors at
Unilever and seven at Tesco, where chairman Sir Ian MacLaurin faces
opposition to his contract from PosTel.
There are seven directors on three-year contracts at Glaxo, including Sir
Richard Sykes, chief executive. The company was yesterday unable to say
which of the directors would be standing for re-election at this year's AGM.
PosTel says that in the past year several large companies have moved from
three-year contracts to two years.
At National Westminster Bank the three-year rolling contracts of Mr Derek
Wanless, chief executive, and five other directors will end in two years'
time and be replaced by one-year rolling contracts.
Of 51 FT-SE 100 companies approached, at least 12 do not have any directors
on three-year contracts.
