<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUN 94 / Investors scheme set to appeal on court ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An emergency board meeting of the Investors Compensation Scheme is expected
to take place this week, amid concern that a Court of Appeal ruling last
Friday could put the scheme's future at risk.
The ICS is likely to decide soon to seek leave to appeal to the Lords
against the terms of the judgment that it was wrong to use its discretion to
limit the amount of compensation paid to investors in home income plans.
What particularly concerns the ICS are the wider implications of the ruling,
which requires the scheme to take all relevant factors into account for each
case, in the same way that a court would.
If the implications of the judgment stand, then the scheme might be
vulnerable to challenge on all the awards it has made - about 6,700.
An ability to exercise discretion in determining a formula for awarding
compensation - for example, in deciding the dates from which claims would be
payable - was written into the ICS rules. The scheme, which is funded by a
levy on the financial services industry, was set up in 1988 to provide a
safety net for investors who are entitled to redress but find that the firm
responsible for their predicament has gone out of business.
Last week's judgment could mean that the scheme has to pay a further Pounds
20m compensation on top of the Pounds 22.5m it has paid to almost 2,000 home
income plan investors. The ICS believes that as well as the potential costs
resulting from a review of other awards, higher administration costs would
be incurred in moving to a more legalistic scheme as a result of the
judgment.
New funding arrangements for the scheme are due to come into effect from
mid-July following a review by the Securities and Investments Board, the
City's chief watchdog. Financial services companies will no longer have to
bail out companies in other sectors of the industry that are unable to meet
their liabilities to investors.
</TEXT>
