<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUN 94 / Tighter absence controls revealed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies have tightened absence controls because of government moves to
shift the cost of sickness benefit from the state to employers, says an
independent employment agency.
Incomes Data Services has found that in spite of government assurances that
lower National Insurance contributions would compensate for the higher
burden on employers of sick pay, many employers still feared that they would
be be inadequately re-imbursed.
The report adds that while a Confederation of British Industry report found
that the cost of absence to UK businesses was Pounds 11bn last year,
equivalent to eight days per employee, companies believe that fear of
redundancy is maintaining a downward pressure on absences.
The report recommends that companies establish formal absence policies
alongside the compilation of regular absence statistics.
Some companies, such as Kodak and Yorkshire Chemicals, have introduced
attendance bonuses for their workforce. Employees at Yorkshire Chemicals can
receive an attendence bonus of up to Pounds 210 a year.
Absence &amp; Sick Pay Policies (IDS Study 556). 193 St John Street, London EC1V
4LS.
