<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUN 94 / World Cup '94: Police facing crutch dilemma
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Security precautions have been intense at each of the nine World Cup venues.
There have been no reports of hooliganism - feared by officials - but a ban
on taking flag-poles and other sharp objects into the
stadiums has not proved successful. New Jersey police have noticed a rise in
leg injuries among spectators.
'People are coming through the gates on crutches, then pulling their flags
from their underwear and flying them from a crutch,' said police spokesman
John Hagerty. 'And we can't do anything,' he said. 'You can't take a guy's
crutches away from him. He might really be injured or disabled.'
