<HEADLINE>
FT  27 JUN 94 / Markets expect banks to support dollar again
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Financial markets expect central banks led by the US Federal Reserve to
repeat early this week - possibly today - their action to lift the dollar
against the D-Mark and the yen.
Shortly after the Tokyo opening today, bankers reported the Bank of Japan
buying dollars at around Y100.1. On Friday the currency closed in New York
at Y100.525. The yen's upward assault caused Tokyo stocks to post early
losses of about 335 points, or 1.62 per cent.
Despite the prospect of support, market analysts were sceptical last night
about whether a re-run of Friday's widescale intervention would be enough to
boost the US currency. If such action failed, it would encourage market
speculation about an imminent rise in US interest rates.
A European monetary official warned yesterday that after years in which US
government officials had displayed a lack of concern about the dollar, the
Fed might be forced into monetary tightening. 'Last Friday the US
authorities showed they care (about the dollar) - a bit,' he said.
The dollar purchases at the end of last week by 17 central banks including
the German Bundesbank failed to lift the currency, which closed on Friday in
New York at DM1.584.
Traders in New York and London were confident at the weekend that
intervention would continue but said this would provide a selling
opportunity for those wanting to offload the currency.
Mr Stephen Flanagan, of New York stockbrokers PaineWebber, said: 'There is
no question that there is an overwhelming amount of bearishness built up
against the dollar.'
Mr Paul Chertkow, global currency analyst at Union Bank of Switzerland in
London, said any further intervention would have to be 'aggressive and
concerted' to stop the dollar falling further. But he said selling of the
dollar so far this month, during which it fell sharply against the D-Mark
and yen, 'has been a long way from an avalanche', with most large
institutional investors on the sidelines.
The Fed is thought to be preoccupied with helping the US economy to recover,
making it less than keen to consider an imminent rise in the short-term
federal funds rate, now 4.25 per cent.
