<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 94 / Sport (World Cup'94): Mexico beat Ireland in Group E
cauldron - Soccer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BERLIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ORLANDO, FLORIDA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mexico's 2-1 win against Ireland yesterday means that four countries are
locked in bitter struggle in the World Cup's toughest group. Luis Garcia
scored both Mexican goals. But John Aldridge's headed goal for Ireland in
the 83rd minute may prove important, reports Peter Berlin from Orlando,
Florida.
All four teams in Group E could still finish in any position. They are level
on points (three) and on goal difference (zero). However, Aldridge's goal
means Ireland at present share first place with Mexico: both have scored
twice while Italy and Norway have scored once each.
In the 44`C sauna of the Citrus Bowl, Ireland waxed and waned. When the sun
hid behind cloud, they ventured forth; when it blazed, they slumped into
defence.
Manager Jack Charlton's latest trick to combat dehydration was plastic
goldfish bags filled with water and tossed out to the players. But as the
game wore on, the heat took its toll.
Ray Houghton on Ireland's right wing was sluggish almost throughout. The
most dangerous Irish threats came from the pacy runs of Terry Phelan. But
Phelan was left leaden-footed in the 44th minute when a Mexican surge saw
the ball laid into Garcia's path.
His low 25-yard shot flew past Pat Bonner's right hand into the corner of
the net. In the 65th minute, Mexico repeated the trick, Alberto Garcia Aspe
skipping past Denis Irwin's indecisive challenge to set up Garcia, who drove
to Bonner's right.
Ireland were on the ropes. The normally unflappable Paul McGrath was left
floundering by Mexico's pace. At the other end, the Irish seemed incapable
of penetrating the Mexican penalty area. Charlton threw on two substitutes
and with only seven minutes left, Ireland stole a precious goal. Jason
McAteer escaped Joaquin Del Olmo and crossed for Aldridge to head down past
Jorge Campos.
'Come on you boys in green,' sang the fans, even though it was Mexico who
were clad in green.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
