<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 94 / Mexican minister offers to quit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Mexican political system was thrown into further disarray yesterday
after Mr Jorge Carpizo, the powerful interior minister, offered to resign.
President Carlos Salinas refused to accept the resignation and, yesterday
afternoon, a government official said it could not be assumed that Mr
Carpizo, who is in charge of national security and supervisor of the
presidential election due in August, would resign.
The minister, a volatile man widely respected for his political
independence, said of his resignation that he was indignant and
disillusioned that 'people in the most diverse sectors (of the country),
despite the current situation of the country, are only fighting for
themselves and for their group, not for Mexico.
'I am beginning not to be respected by one of the (political) parties, given
that I cannot agree with the actions of some sectors of this party.'
Mr Carpizo did not name the party but, in recent weeks, he has been angered
by criticism from the leftist Party of Democratic Revolution of the fairness
of the electoral system. He believes that this has called into question his
own honesty and impartiality.
Even so, Mr Carpizo's indignation with 'diverse sectors' of society
indicates a frustration almost certainly extended to parts of the government
and the ruling party, the PRI. Mr Carpizo has long been opposed by
conservative forces in the party.
The lawyer for Mr Alfredo Harp Helu, the kidnapped Mexican financier, has
said on national television that his ransom would be paid, paving the way
for his release within three days. Mr Harp, joint head of Banamex-Accival,
the largest bank in Mexico, was seized in March.
The kidnappers said in their latest communication that the ransom demand had
been dropped to less than Dollars 30m (Pounds 19.5m). The lawyer agreed to
pay an unspecified amount.
</TEXT>
<XX>
