<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 94 / Californian vote on immigrants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEREMY KAHN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Illegal immigrants in California will be denied public education, healthcare
and other services if the state accepts an initiative which will be on
ballot papers in November. It would also require police, teachers and
healthcare workers to report suspected illegal immigrants to federal
authorities. The outcome of the vote might point the way for other US
states, such as Florida and New York, which also have many illegal aliens,
Jeremy Kahn writes from Washington.
Californian state officials confirmed that backers of the proposal - called
the Save Our State initiative - had collected more than the 600,000
signatures necessary to put the issue to a state-wide referendum.
Governor Pete Wilson of California, the incumbent Republican who is running
for re-election in November but trails in the opinion polls, endorsed the
initiative last week. Mr Wilson's Democratic opponent, Ms Kathleen Brown,
opposes the proposal, as do various prominent civil rights and Latino
groups.
These critics have labelled the initiative discriminatory and racist, as it
primarily targets Hispanic and Asian minorities. They have promised to
challenge the proposal on constitutional grounds if it wins a majority.
</TEXT>
