<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JUN 94 / UK set to veto Dehaene as EC president: Summit deadlock over
successor to Delors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CORFU
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major signalled early today he was ready to veto the appointment of
Mr Jean-Luc Dehaene to succeed Mr Jacques Delors as president of the
European Commission, in spite of a Franco-German bandwagon in favour of the
Belgian premier.
Leaders of the 12 European Union countries failed to reach agreement on the
key Brussels job on the first day of their summit in Corfu, but will
reconvene later today for further discussion.
Senior British officials said there were 'no circumstances' in which Mr
Major would accept Mr Dehaene. The officials said the Belgian premier did
not command the necessary consensus within the EU. 'In our view he does not
fit the bill,' one high-ranking official said.
If the present Greek presidency of the EU continued to press Mr Dehaene's
candidacy, Mr Major was ready to use his government's veto to block it,
officials indicated. He would stick to this line if the issue was deferred
to another summit next month.
The British stand threw into confusion the whole question of who will take
over from Mr Delors. After a day of behind-the-scenes argument, a clash at a
summit dinner and a brief recall for emergency talks in the early hours of
this morning, only Britain and the Netherlands were still holding out
against Mr Dehaene.
Spain and Italy initially joined the Netherlands in backing Mr Ruud Lubbers,
the outgoing Dutch premier, but later switched to Mr Dehaene.
Mr Lubbers refused to withdraw from the race even though 10 member states
were eventually supporting Mr Dehaene.
Mr Major, under intense pressure from Tory Eurosceptics in the UK to veto
the appointment of the avowed Belgian federalist, was isolated in promoting
the candidacy of Sir Leon Brittan, the EU trade commissioner.
British officials said that if Sir Leon withdrew, Mr Major was ready to
support Mr Lubbers.
Mr Dehaene's candidacy was overshadowed by widespread irritation at the way
Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany had sought to control the succession to Mr
Delors and by the confused handling of debate by the Greek presidency of the
EU.
Mr Douglas Hurd, UK foreign secretary, attacked the handling of the
negotiations and, in a thinly veiled rebuke to Bonn and Paris, commented:
'There is a lot of poison around. The atmosphere is not good. The problem is
not so much with the three candidates but with the way the whole issue has
been handled.'
German officials insisted that Mr Dehaene was the overwhelming favourite and
that this left the UK and the Netherlands no option but to withdraw.
Mr Kohl has threatened a second summit next month if the deadlock continues
beyond the Corfu meeting, which is due to end this afternoon. But he
predicted yesterday: 'We'll be able to settle this problem.'
Other member states were more reserved, underlining that the candidate
required unanimous backing and that front-runners in previous successions
have been vetoed.
Mr Delors himself owes his job to a veto by Lady Thatcher, the former
British prime minister, in 1984 against the then French foreign minister Mr
Claude Cheysson.
Summit reports, Pages 2-3
Seeing red and orange, Page 24
Union Jacques, Weekend, Page I
</TEXT>
<XX>
